  <POU Name="PRG_CMMT_AS" Id="{bbd6a5c8-f8db-448d-b188-8add5d730760}" SpecialFunc="None">
    <Declaration><![CDATA[PROGRAM PRG_CMMT_AS
VAR
	
stCMMT_In : ST_CMMT_DriveToPlc;
END_VAR
]]></Declaration>
    <Implementation>
      <ST><![CDATA[(*


// EtherCAT DIP Switch Configuration
SW1    SW2    SW3
 0      1      0
OFF     ON    OFF



Beckhoff EtherCAT master
          │
          ▼
CMMT-AS [XF1 IN]
CMMT-AS [XF2 OUT]
          │
          ▼
Next EtherCAT slave

*)

(*
CMMT-AS — CiA 402 motion start behaviour

```
There is no separate universal "Start" PDO.

The function of Controlword bits 4...6 depends on the operating
mode selected with object 6060h "Modes of operation".

Always wait until object 6061h "Modes of operation display"
confirms the requested mode before issuing a motion command.

---------------------------------------------------------------
MODE 1 — PROFILE POSITION
---------------------------------------------------------------

6060h := 1

The CMMT generates the position trajectory internally.

Before starting:
  1. Write Target position 607Ah.
  2. Write Profile velocity 6081h.
  3. Write acceleration/deceleration, when required.
  4. Make sure Controlword bit 4 is FALSE.

Start positioning with a rising edge of Controlword bit 4:

    Bit 4: FALSE -> TRUE

Relevant Controlword bits:
  Bit 4 = New set-point / start positioning
  Bit 5 = Change set-point immediately
  Bit 6 = 0: absolute position
          1: relative position
  Bit 8 = Halt

Position-command handshake:
  1. Set bit 4.
  2. Wait for Statusword bit 12 = TRUE
     (set-point acknowledged).
  3. Clear Controlword bit 4.
  4. Wait for Statusword bit 12 = FALSE.
  5. Wait for Statusword bit 10 = TRUE
     (target reached).

Merely changing Target position 607Ah does not start a movement.
A new FALSE-to-TRUE transition of Controlword bit 4 is required
for every new positioning command.

---------------------------------------------------------------
MODE 3 — PROFILE VELOCITY / JOG
---------------------------------------------------------------

6060h := 3

There is no separate Start bit in Profile Velocity mode.

Movement is controlled directly by Target velocity 60FFh:

    Target velocity > 0  : move in positive direction
    Target velocity < 0  : move in negative direction
    Target velocity = 0  : decelerate to standstill

Therefore, jogging is active while a non-zero signed target
velocity is being commanded.

Controlword bit 8 may be used to request Halt.

Before changing from Profile Velocity to another mode:
  1. Command Target velocity := 0.
  2. Wait until actual velocity is approximately zero.
  3. Select the new mode in 6060h.
  4. Wait until 6061h confirms the new mode.

---------------------------------------------------------------
MODE 6 — HOMING
---------------------------------------------------------------

6060h := 6

The homing method, direction, speeds and acceleration are
configured in Festo Automation Suite or through parameters.

Start homing with a rising edge of Controlword bit 4:

    Bit 4: FALSE -> TRUE

Relevant Statusword bits:
  Bit 12 = Homing attained
  Bit 13 = Homing error

Keep the homing-start command active while homing is running,
then clear Controlword bit 4 after homing has completed or failed.

---------------------------------------------------------------
IMPORTANT
---------------------------------------------------------------

Controlword bits 4...6 must never be interpreted without first
considering the active operating mode.

The same physical bit can have a different function in:
  Mode 1: Profile Position
  Mode 3: Profile Velocity
  Mode 6: Homing
  Mode 8: Cyclic Synchronous Position

Mode 8 must not be used for simple direct PLC positioning unless
the PLC continuously generates cyclic trajectory set-points.
```

*)







(*

Reading brake status The values of 2150:05 are: Value Meaning 0 Brake closed 1 Brake open 2 Brake opening 3 Brake closing

*)



(*
    =====================================================================
    CMMT-AS HOLDING BRAKE CONTROL
    =====================================================================

    EtherCAT / CoE objects used:

        60FE:01    Digital outputs
        60FE:02    Digital output mask
        2150:05    Holding brake 1 status

    Brake release command:

        60FE:01 bit 0 = 1
            Request the holding brake to release/open.

        60FE:01 bit 0 = 0
            Remove the holding-brake release request.

    Output control mask:

        60FE:02 bit 0 = 1
            The fieldbus/PLC controls bit 0 of 60FE:01.

        60FE:02 bit 0 = 0
            The fieldbus/PLC does not control this output bit.

    IMPORTANT:

    The command is called "Brake Release Request" because the PLC is
    requesting that the CMMT releases the brake. It is not direct proof
    that the mechanical brake is physically open.

    For a vertical axis, releasing the brake without motor torque or
    mechanical support can allow the load to fall.

    The manual brake-release command should normally be restricted to
    commissioning, maintenance or service operation.

    During normal automatic motion, the CMMT should normally coordinate:

        Motor torque enabled
        -> brake released
        -> movement allowed

    and:

        Movement stopped
        -> brake applied
        -> motor torque disabled
    =====================================================================
*)


{attribute 'qualified_only'}
TYPE E_CMMT_BrakeStatus :
(
    Closed  := 0,    // Brake is reported closed/applied
    Open    := 1,    // Brake is reported open/released
    Opening := 2,    // Brake is currently opening
    Closing := 3,    // Brake is currently closing

    Invalid := 4     // Value received from drive is not recognised
);
END_TYPE


FUNCTION_BLOCK FB_CMMT_BrakeControl
VAR_INPUT
    (*
        Enables control of the brake-release-request PDO bit.

        FALSE:
            The FB clears bit 0 of the output mask.
            The PLC does not request control of the brake-release bit.

        TRUE:
            The FB sets bit 0 of 60FE:02.
            The PLC controls bit 0 of 60FE:01.

        For a manual/service brake-release function, this input would
        normally be enabled only while the machine is in an authorised
        service or commissioning mode.
    *)
    i_bEnableManualBrakeControl : BOOL;


    (*
        Operator or application request to release the holding brake.

        FALSE:
            No manual release request.

        TRUE:
            Request the CMMT to release/open the holding brake.

        This input does not bypass i_bReleasePermitted.
    *)
    i_bManualBrakeRelease : BOOL;


    (*
        Application interlock permitting brake release.

        Suggested conditions for a vertical axis include:

            - Safety system permits movement
            - Axis is mechanically supported, or motor torque is established
            - Machine is in an authorised operating mode
            - No active brake-related fault
            - No conflicting stop or emergency command

        The FB only issues the release request when this input is TRUE.
    *)
    i_bReleasePermitted : BOOL;


    (*
        Raw brake status received from object 2150:05.

        Expected values:

            0 = Brake closed
            1 = Brake open
            2 = Brake opening
            3 = Brake closing
    *)
    i_udiBrakeStatusRaw : UDINT;
END_VAR


VAR_IN_OUT
    (*
        Object 60FE:01 — Digital outputs.

        Only bit 0 is modified by this FB.
        All other bits are preserved.
    *)
    io_udiDigitalOutputs : UDINT;


    (*
        Object 60FE:02 — Digital output mask.

        Only bit 0 is modified by this FB.
        All other mask bits are preserved.
    *)
    io_udiDigitalOutputsMask : UDINT;
END_VAR


VAR_OUTPUT
    (*
        TRUE when the PLC currently owns the brake-release bit and is
        actively sending a release request.
    *)
    o_bReleaseRequestActive : BOOL;


    (*
        Decoded brake status.
    *)
    o_eBrakeStatus : E_CMMT_BrakeStatus;


    (*
        Individual status outputs for simple use in application logic
        and HMI displays.
    *)
    o_bBrakeClosed  : BOOL;
    o_bBrakeOpen    : BOOL;
    o_bBrakeOpening : BOOL;
    o_bBrakeClosing : BOOL;


    (*
        TRUE while the brake is either opening or closing.
    *)
    o_bBrakeTransitioning : BOOL;


    (*
        TRUE when 2150:05 contains one of the documented values 0...3.

        FALSE means that an unexpected value was received.
    *)
    o_bBrakeStatusValid : BOOL;


    (*
        TRUE when the operator requested brake release, but an application
        interlock prevented the request from being sent.
    *)
    o_bReleaseRequestBlocked : BOOL;
END_VAR


VAR
    (*
        Final internally calculated release request.

        The EtherCAT command is only issued when all three conditions
        are TRUE.
    *)
    bReleaseRequest : BOOL;
END_VAR


VAR CONSTANT
    (*
        Bit mask for bit 0.

        This bit is used in both:

            60FE:01 Digital outputs
            60FE:02 Digital output mask
    *)
    C_UDI_BRAKE_RELEASE : UDINT := 16#00000001;
END_VAR


(*
    =====================================================================
    CALCULATE THE FINAL BRAKE-RELEASE REQUEST
    =====================================================================

    The request is accepted only when:

        1. Manual brake control is enabled.
        2. A brake-release request is present.
        3. The application permits brake release.
*)
bReleaseRequest :=
    i_bEnableManualBrakeControl
    AND i_bManualBrakeRelease
    AND i_bReleasePermitted;


(*
    Indicate when the requested operation has been blocked by an
    application interlock.

    This can be displayed on the HMI to explain why pressing the
    brake-release button did not release the brake.
*)
o_bReleaseRequestBlocked :=
    i_bEnableManualBrakeControl
    AND i_bManualBrakeRelease
    AND NOT i_bReleasePermitted;


(*
    =====================================================================
    CONTROL 60FE:02 — DIGITAL OUTPUT MASK
    =====================================================================

    Setting bit 0 in the mask gives the fieldbus/PLC control over
    bit 0 of 60FE:01.

    OR is used instead of direct assignment so that any other output-mask
    bits used elsewhere in the application are not overwritten.
*)
IF i_bEnableManualBrakeControl THEN

    io_udiDigitalOutputsMask :=
        io_udiDigitalOutputsMask OR C_UDI_BRAKE_RELEASE;

ELSE

    (*
        Remove PLC control of the brake-release-request bit.

        AND NOT clears only bit 0 and preserves all other mask bits.
    *)
    io_udiDigitalOutputsMask :=
        io_udiDigitalOutputsMask AND (NOT C_UDI_BRAKE_RELEASE);

END_IF


(*
    =====================================================================
    CONTROL 60FE:01 — BRAKE RELEASE REQUEST
    =====================================================================

    Bit 0 = 1:
        Request the holding brake to open/release.

    Bit 0 = 0:
        Remove the manual release request.

    OR and AND NOT are used so that all other digital-output bits remain
    unchanged.
*)
IF bReleaseRequest THEN

    io_udiDigitalOutputs :=
        io_udiDigitalOutputs OR C_UDI_BRAKE_RELEASE;

ELSE

    io_udiDigitalOutputs :=
        io_udiDigitalOutputs AND (NOT C_UDI_BRAKE_RELEASE);

END_IF


(*
    Confirm the command that is actually present in the PDO data.

    Both conditions must be true:

        - Output mask bit 0 is enabled.
        - Digital output bit 0 is set.
*)
o_bReleaseRequestActive :=
    ((io_udiDigitalOutputsMask AND C_UDI_BRAKE_RELEASE) <> 0)
    AND
    ((io_udiDigitalOutputs AND C_UDI_BRAKE_RELEASE) <> 0);


(*
    =====================================================================
    INITIALISE BRAKE STATUS OUTPUTS
    =====================================================================

    Outputs are reset every PLC cycle before decoding the status.

    This prevents an old TRUE state from remaining latched when the
    drive changes to another brake state.
*)
o_eBrakeStatus          := E_CMMT_BrakeStatus.Invalid;

o_bBrakeClosed          := FALSE;
o_bBrakeOpen            := FALSE;
o_bBrakeOpening         := FALSE;
o_bBrakeClosing         := FALSE;
o_bBrakeTransitioning   := FALSE;
o_bBrakeStatusValid     := FALSE;


(*
    =====================================================================
    DECODE 2150:05 — HOLDING BRAKE 1 STATUS
    =====================================================================

        Value 0:
            Brake closed/applied.

        Value 1:
            Brake open/released.

        Value 2:
            Brake opening.

        Value 3:
            Brake closing.

    The opening and closing states are transitional states.
*)
CASE i_udiBrakeStatusRaw OF

    0:
        (*
            Brake closed/applied.

            The drive reports that the brake-control sequence has reached
            the closed state.
        *)
        o_eBrakeStatus      := E_CMMT_BrakeStatus.Closed;
        o_bBrakeClosed      := TRUE;
        o_bBrakeStatusValid := TRUE;


    1:
        (*
            Brake open/released.

            The drive reports that the brake-control sequence has reached
            the open state.
        *)
        o_eBrakeStatus      := E_CMMT_BrakeStatus.Open;
        o_bBrakeOpen        := TRUE;
        o_bBrakeStatusValid := TRUE;


    2:
        (*
            Brake opening.

            The CMMT is currently executing the configured brake-opening
            sequence or brake-release delay.
        *)
        o_eBrakeStatus          := E_CMMT_BrakeStatus.Opening;
        o_bBrakeOpening         := TRUE;
        o_bBrakeTransitioning   := TRUE;
        o_bBrakeStatusValid     := TRUE;


    3:
        (*
            Brake closing.

            The CMMT is currently executing the configured brake-closing
            sequence or brake-application delay.
        *)
        o_eBrakeStatus          := E_CMMT_BrakeStatus.Closing;
        o_bBrakeClosing         := TRUE;
        o_bBrakeTransitioning   := TRUE;
        o_bBrakeStatusValid     := TRUE;


ELSE
    (*
        Unexpected or unsupported value.

        This can indicate:

            - Incorrect PDO mapping
            - Incorrect data type
            - Incorrect byte alignment
            - Firmware/object-version mismatch
            - Invalid data while EtherCAT is not operational
    *)
    o_eBrakeStatus      := E_CMMT_BrakeStatus.Invalid;
    o_bBrakeStatusValid := FALSE;

END_CASE
```

## Example call from `MAIN`

```iecst
PROGRAM MAIN
VAR
    fbCMMTBrake : FB_CMMT_BrakeControl;

    // Command from HMI or service controls.
    bManualBrakeRelease : BOOL;

    // Recommended release interlocks.
    bServiceMode               : BOOL;
    bSafetyPermitsRelease      : BOOL;
    bAxisMechanicallySupported : BOOL;
END_VAR


(*
    Example for a vertical axis.

    The brake release is permitted only when:

        - The machine is in service mode.
        - The safety system permits the operation.
        - The vertical load is mechanically supported.

    Replace these conditions with the interlocks appropriate for your
    machine risk assessment.
*)
fbCMMTBrake(
    i_bEnableManualBrakeControl := bServiceMode,

    i_bManualBrakeRelease       := bManualBrakeRelease,

    i_bReleasePermitted         :=
        bSafetyPermitsRelease
        AND bAxisMechanicallySupported,

    // Object 2150:05 from the CMMT input PDO.
    i_udiBrakeStatusRaw         := stCMMT_In.udiBrake1Status,

    // Objects 60FE:01 and 60FE:02 in the CMMT output PDO.
    io_udiDigitalOutputs        := stCMMT_Out.udiDigitalOutputs,
    io_udiDigitalOutputsMask    := stCMMT_Out.udiDigitalOutputsMask
);
```


CASE stCMMT_In.udiBrake1Status OF
    0:
        o_bBrakeClosed  := TRUE;
        o_bBrakeOpen    := FALSE;
        o_bBrakeMoving  := FALSE;

    1:
        o_bBrakeClosed  := FALSE;
        o_bBrakeOpen    := TRUE;
        o_bBrakeMoving  := FALSE;

    2:
        o_bBrakeClosed  := FALSE;
        o_bBrakeOpen    := FALSE;
        o_bBrakeMoving  := TRUE;     // Opening

    3:
        o_bBrakeClosed  := FALSE;
        o_bBrakeOpen    := FALSE;
        o_bBrakeMoving  := TRUE;     // Closing

ELSE
    o_bBrakeClosed  := FALSE;
    o_bBrakeOpen    := FALSE;
    o_bBrakeMoving  := FALSE;
END_CASE;]]></ST>
    </Implementation>
  </POU>
